1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 e5 5. Nb5 a6 {This variation is known
to give White a slight advantage. However, Black has come up with some
improvements lately, so I am not sure that this assessment is completely
correct. It is also very tricky to play White if you are unprepared as there
are several traps to walk into.} 6. Nd6+ Bxd6 7. Qxd6 Qf6 8. Qc7 {This is
White's safest option as it forces Black into a slightly worse endgame, with
no need to take any risks for White. The drawback is that Black, after a long
and insistent defence, usually holds the draw.} (8. Qxf6 {is not very
ambitious. After} Nxf6 9. Nc3 Nb4 {Black has already equalised.}) ({the
alternatives are} 8. Qd1) (8. Qd2 {and}) (8. Qa3 {but they all give Black
plenty of counterplay after either ...Qg6 followed by ...Nf6/...d5 or ...Nge7
followed by ...0-0 and ...d5.}) 8... Nge7 (8... Qg6 9. Nc3 Nf6 {has also been
played, but after} 10. Qd6 $1 {preventing ...d5 White has at least a slight
edge. Black is struggling both with his queenside development and to castle.})
9. Nc3 Nb4 10. Bd3 O-O $2 {This is already a mistake as now White will get a
much better version of the usual variation that follows after} (10... d5 11.
O-O (11. Bd2 {was played in Berg-Mirzoev, Soller 2006. But after} d4 12. Na4
Qc6 13. Qxc6+ Nexc6 14. Nb6 Rb8 15. f4 f6 16. f5 Kd8 17. a3 Nxd3+ 18. cxd3 Kc7
19. Nd5+ Kd6 20. O-O Bd7 21. Nb6 Kc7 22. Nd5+ Kd6 23. a4 a5 24. Nb6 Kc7 25.
Nd5+ Kd6 26. Rab1 b5 {1/2-1/2 Berg,E (2540)-Mirzoev,A (2498)/Soller 2006/CBM
110 ext (47). Black had managed to equalize and later on the game turned into
a draw.}) 11... d4 12. Na4 Qc6 13. Qxc6+ Nexc6 14. Nb6 Rb8 15. Bd2 Be6 16. a3 (
{After} 16. f4 {Black has the strong reply} Nxd3 17. cxd3 f5 $1 18. fxe5 O-O
19. Bf4 fxe4 20. dxe4 d3 {with compensation for the sacrificed pawn.}) 16...
Nxd3 17. cxd3 {with some advantage to White because of the strongly placed
knight on b6.}) 11. O-O d5 12. f4 $1 {A strong move that forces Black into
passivity.} Nxd3 13. cxd3 d4 14. Na4 ({After the tempting} 14. fxe5 {Black has
the defensive resource} Qc6 $1 15. Qxe7 dxc3 {and Black looks fine.}) 14... Bg4
$1 ({After} 14... Qc6 15. Qxe7 Qxa4 16. Qxe5 {White is a pawn up and has a
clear advantage.}) 15. Nb6 Rae8 (15... Rad8 $5) 16. Rf2 {Preventing ...Be2 and
activating the threat f4-f5 to trap the black bishop. White has a clear
advantage, but as the game will show Black is still rather solid. Perhaps
playing more energetically with} (16. b3 $5 {with the idea of Ba3 would have
been even stronger. If Black tries} Be2 {White will counter with} 17. Nd7 Qc6 (
17... Qh4 18. Rf2 Bxd3 19. Nxf8 Kxf8 20. Qxe5 $18) 18. Qxc6 bxc6 (18... Nxc6 {
runs into trouble after} 19. Rf2 Bxd3 20. Ba3 $1 {with a winning advantage to
White.}) 19. Re1 Bxd3 20. Nxe5 $1 Bc2 21. Nd7 $18 {with a clear exchange up to
White.}) 16... Qc6 17. Qxc6 Nxc6 18. h3 {forcing back the bishop to its
original square.} (18. f5 {wins an exchange by force after} f6 19. h3 Bh5 20.
g4 Bf7 21. Nd7 {but after} Nb4 {Black gets plenty of counterplay.} 22. Rd2 Nxa2
(22... Bxa2 $2 23. Nxf8 Kxf8 24. b3 $1 Bxb3 25. Rb2) 23. Nxf8 Rxf8 $44) 18...
Bc8 19. f5 f6 20. b3 Rd8 21. Ba3 (21. a4 $5 {looks a bit better not to waste
any time with Bc5 as in the game.}) 21... Rf7 22. Rc1 Bd7 23. Bc5 {Planning a4
to take control over the b5-square.} Nb8 {Black starts to re-route his pieces.
Now ...Bb5 followed by ...Nd7 is a threat.} 24. a4 Bc6 {Now Black threatens ..
Nd7 forcing a exchange of knights which would result in a drawish endgame.} 25.
Bb4 {White prepares to answer ...Nd7 with Nc4, but also makes the bishop more
flexible and opens the c-file for his rook.} Nd7 26. Nc4 Nb8 27. Nb6 Nd7 28.
Nc4 Nb8 29. Rfc2 g6 30. Ba5 Rdf8 31. Bb4 Rd8 32. Rf2 {White is about to take
on g6 and put heavy pressure on the f-file with Rcf1.} gxf5 (32... g5 {does
not solve Black's problems. After} 33. Rfc2 {White will continue his
manoeuvring work on the queenside and Black his tough defensive task.}) 33.
Rxf5 Bd7 34. Rf2 Be6 35. Rcf1 Bxc4 {Black has finally managed to exchange off
the strong white knight, but White still has a a strong bishop against a bad
knight.} 36. bxc4 Nd7 37. g4 Rg7 (37... h5 38. gxh5 $14) 38. Rf5 Kf7 39. Kf2
Rg5 $2 {This move forces White to take an important decision on the last move
before the time-control. But after what follows this turns out to be a mistake
from Black's side and White makes a lot of progress.} (39... Kg6 {would have
been better, allthough Black still has a long way to a draw.}) 40. Rxg5 $1 {
This move may seem to help Black as he no longer has the weakness on f6. But
the truth is that now he gets two new weaknesses in the pawns on e5 and g5.}
fxg5 41. Ke2+ Kg6 $2 (41... Ke6 {was necessary. White should continue} 42. Bd2
h6 43. h4 Rg8 44. hxg5 hxg5 45. Rh1 {and the white rook will soon enter on
either the h- or the b-file.} (45. Rf5 $2 {is not good enough after} Rh8 $1 (
45... Nf6 {is well met by} 46. Rxg5 Rxg5 47. Bxg5 Nxg4 $4 (47... Nd7 48. Bd2
$16) 48. Kf3 Nh2+ 49. Kg2 Ng4 50. Kg3 Ne3 (50... Nf6 51. Bxf6 Kxf6 52. Kg4 Kg6
53. a5 Kf6 54. Kh5 Ke6 55. Kg5 b6 56. axb6 Kd6 57. Kf5 a5 58. b7 Kc7 59. Kxe5
a4 60. Kxd4 $18) 51. Bxe3 dxe3 52. Kf3 Kd6 53. Kxe3 Kc5 54. d4+ exd4+ 55. Kd3
$18))) 42. Bd6 $1 {A very important move that forces the black pieces to the
defence of the e5-pawn.} Rc8 (42... b6 43. a5 $16) 43. Rf5 Re8 (43... b5 44.
axb5 axb5 45. cxb5 $16) 44. a5 Re6 45. c5 Re8 46. Kd1 h6 47. Kd2 $22 {Black is
in zugzwang} Rd8 (47... Kg7 48. Rf1 Rc8 49. Rb1 Nxc5 50. Bxe5+ $18) (47... Re6
48. Kc2 Re8 49. Kb3 $18 {and the white king will penetrate via c4-d5 with
total domination.[%csl Gb3][%cal Yb3c4,Yc4d5]}) 48. Bxe5 Nxc5 49. Rf6+ Kh7 50.
Rf7+ Kg8 51. Rg7+ Kf8 52. Rh7 Ke8 53. Rxh6 ({Also possible was} 53. Rh8+ Kd7
54. Rxd8+ Kxd8 55. Bxd4 $18 {as after} Nb3+ 56. Kc3 {the a5-pawn is tactically
protected.}) 53... Kf7 54. Rf6+ Ke8 55. Rh6 Kf7 56. Rf6+ Ke8 57. Rg6 Kf7 58.
Rxg5 Nb3+ 59. Kc2 Nxa5 60. Bxd4 {Black resigned as the upcoming rook endgame
with two pawns down is totally hopeless.} 1-0

